deck_excerpt: Hanzo and Therizia sitting under a tree...
deck_description: As far as Master Duel goes, we still have a long way to go until we get the Ninja support from Darkwing Blast, until then Ninjas will remain just Hanzo and a few Ninjitsu traps plus other engines plus staples, since pure Ninjas is beyond bad at the moment. To make the wait more exciting, Ninjas now have a new engine to play with, while in the past I put Hanzo alongside Albaz and Dogmatika Ecclesia, now I'm making Hanzo tag along with Therizia, both very similar cards as they are level 4 dark monsters that search a trap on summon. Beyond that, the synergy between both archetypes is that Ninjitsu Art of Super-Transformation can send Hanzo and an opponent's monster to summon Therizia and get the Dinomorphia engine going. All of this is now viable because of Dinomorphia Rexterm and Dinomorphia Frenzy, the newly released cards from Beginning of Turmoil; before these cards came out it was pretty difficult to run Dinomorphia cards in anything other than a pure build.

deck_excerpt: Penguins and Icejades team up to control the field!
deck_description:
Penguins and Icejades may not seem like they have much in common, but they actually complement each other so well, it's as if they were made to be played together!

 

To quickly summarize both archetypes: 

Icejades are a defensive deck that primarily focuses on stalling and floodgating. They do this through three key cards: the field spell Icejade Cenote Enion Cradle, the spell Icejade Curse, and their boss monster Icejade Kosmochlor. The archetype's searcher, Icejade Cradle, is not once per turn.

Penguins are a control deck that focuses on interruptions and banishing your opponent's resources. The key cards are The Great Emperor Penguin, Penguin Brave, and the OG Penguin Soldier.

 

Important cards:

1. Icejade Aegirine - This girl carries her whole archetype on her back by allowing you essentially search any Icejade card. She also has an effect where if she's targeted for an attack or an effect, she can Special Summon any Water monster from your hand or GY. Notable candidates include Glacial Beast Polar Penguin (for a targeted bounce), Adamancipator Risen - Dragite (for a free negate), The Great Emperor Penguin (to go into the main Penguin combo as I'll mention later), or Icejade Kosmochlor (if you have the field spell).

2. The Great Emperor Penguin - A better Rescue Cat but for Penguins only. Not once per turn, so he's an extremely valuable resource. Searchable with Royal Penguins Garden.

 

Here are a few plays that I find myself doing frequently:

0. The main Penguin combo line: Summon The Great Emperor Penguin and use its effect to summon Nopenguin and Glacial Beast Polar Penguin. Synchro Summon into Penguin Brave and use its effect to summon Penguin Soldier facedown for two bounces. Nopenguin will also chainblock Penguin Brave to summon itself from the GY and turn Soldier's bounces into banishes. This is the main Penguin play, but if you have Penguin Squire in hand, activate its effect when Penguin Soldier is summoned to SS itself. Then Synchro into Adamancipator Risen - Dragite . Nopenguin will come back next turn when you activate Penguin Brave's effect, bringing the banish effect live again.

0.1 There are multiple ways to get out The Great Emperor Penguin. Royal Penguins Garden and Icejade Tremora are the easiest ways. Tremora herself can be searched by Icejade Cradle, which in turn can be searched by Aegirine. Aegirine's Quick Effect can also summon Emperor if the conditions are met.

1. Normal Summon Icejade Aegirine. If you have the field spell, search Icejade Curse if you are going first, Icejade Cradle if you are going second and use Cradle to get Icejade Kosmochlor. If you do not have the field spell, but have The Great Emperor Penguin in hand, search Cradle to get Tremora. Then do the main Penguin line from above.

1.1 The Icejade lockdown is essentially a one-sided Skill Drain. While it's rare to get all three key cards in your starting hand, Icejade Curse does not specifically require Kosmochlor. Therefore, if you are going first and have the field spell and Aegirine in hand, I recommend grabbing Curse to prevent your opponent from using monster effects on the field next turn.

2. Marincess Coral Anemone is an excellent Link-2 monster that can SS any Water monster from your GY with 1500 or less attack. I recommend Summoning her on your second turn to recur some resources. Candidates include Icejade Aegirine to continue setting up your floodgate, Glacial Beast Polar Penguin to bounce and go into Penguin Brave, or Icejade Kosmochlor.

3. Penguin Sword is an Equip spell that can only be equipped to a Penguin. Thus, it's not very recommended in a hybrid deck like this one. However, the effect of Penguin Sword is extremely powerful, so it's a fun option if you choose to run it. It's searchable with Royal Penguins Garden.

4. The side deck contains other options you can try teching in. Icejade Tinola can Special Summon from the GY in a pinch. Nightmare Penguin can be used instead of Soldier to bounce any 1 card rather than 2 monsters, and allows you to access the Rank 4 pool with Squire. Icejade Gymir Aegirine isn't released yet but will be an excellent boss monster, and Icejade Erosion can negate a monster at the cost of an Icejade on the field.

There's a lot more plays that what I've written here, so have fun!
Created and popularized by the legend Karpath.

deck_excerpt: Prepare to experience power like no other!
deck_description:
One of the frustrating things about the Egyptian God cards is how far short they fall from their anime appearances. We all want to summon Slifer the Sky Dragon and feel like we’ve just called forth an ancient and unstoppable force, and then our opponent plays Lightning Storm and that’s the end of that.

            This was certainly how I felt before something called The Tin of the Pharaoh’s Gods came out. Like many duelists, I rejoiced in the release of King’s Court, and how neatly it supported the coolest Egyptian God (these are facts).

Joker's Straight into Thunderspeed Summon, and behold: Slifer the Executive Producer, summoned just like Yugi himself did it, more or less. Joker's Straight returns itself to hand to keep Slifer’s attack up, and his second mouth obliterates just about any monster your opponent has the audacity to summon.

            But, while Slifer is now easier to use than ever before, that doesn’t change the unfortunate fact that he’s not actually that difficult to deal with. His automatic attack is good monster disruption, but he still dies to Raigeki. I used to play three Mound of the Bound Creators, a Terraforming, and a Metaverse, just to try and grant Slifer the protection that I felt a Divine-Beast deserved.

            However, now that we have the Tin of the Pharaoh’s Gods, and the trap card The Revived Sky God, there’s a whole new way to play said Sky God. Now, it’s okay if Slifer is destroyed—that’s all part of the plan.

            Instead of going to the effort to summon Slifer and then getting frustrated by just how easily he dies, you can let him die, knowing he’ll be back and stronger than ever—for one turn. And then another, after that.

            Just for fun, let’s take a look at the absolute best-case scenario:

            Foolish Burial on Slifer—set your whole hand (including The Revived Sky God)—end turn. The instant your opponent draws, flip your trap and resurrect Slifer. You draw six cards, and your opponent, with their full hand, gets nothing. Slifer looms large at 6,000 ATK, torching any monster that raises its unworthy head in his divine presence. At the end of your opponent’s turn, Slifer returns to the Graveyard, and you activate The Revived Sky God’s in-Graveyard effect: stack Monster Reborn to the top of your deck, and then draw one card (if Slifer (any DIVINE monster, technically) is in your Graveyard (which he is)).

            That means when you do draw, you’ll have eight cards in hand, and one of them will be Monster Reborn. Let’s say another is Thunderforce Attack—Reborn the Monster on Slifer, Thunderforce to clear your opponent’s board (if they managed to build one under Slifer’s scrutiny), and draw a card for every monster you destroy, and then attack for game.

            Glorious.

            If you somehow fail to draw an absolutely perfect hand, then the way to play the deck is as a straight King’s Court deck: get those knights on the field, and fuse, link, or tribute them into one of the big Joker boss monsters. Don’t force Slifer into the game; let him show up when he’s ready.

            Some notes about playing the King’s Court cards:

            You have three Joker's Straights, and this is the most important card in the deck. Everything hinges on having King’s, Queen’s, and Jack’s Knights on the field, and that’s what Joker's Straight does for you. Joker's Wild works as a backup Joker's Straight, as well as being able to stand in for Thunderspeed Summon and Face Card Fusion. Both Joker's Straight and Joker's Wild will return themselves to your hand endlessly, in addition to returning Knights from GY to deck.

            Joker's Knight can be Special Summoned as Queen's Knight, and then if you Normal Summon King's Knight, he will warp Jack's Knight onto the field.

            Thunderspeed Summon is for Slifer, but it can also be used to summon Arcana Triumph Joker, who has a useful card-destroying ability: discard any type of card, and destroy all opponent’s cards of that type (Monster, Spell, or Trap). Thunderspeed Summon is also a Quick-Play, which does afford you the opportunity to use it as a combat trick: you can attack with all three knights, and then tribute them to call forth Slifer and attack with him as well.

            Arcana Extra Joker is easy to summon, it replaces itself when it dies, and it protects any monster it’s pointing to from being targeted. This is something to keep in mind when it comes time to summon Slifer; while this deck ideally runs on the premise of recurring Slifer out of the GY with The Revived Sky God and Monster Reborn, sometimes things fall short of the ideal, and we need backup plans.

            The Revived Sky God, like The Breaking Ruin God, aims to set you up for one big, potentially game-ending move with an Egyptian God card. This alternate way of playing the Divine-Beasts is most welcome as far as I’m concerned. In the anime, the very summoning of any God card usually meant the game would be over that turn. That seems to be what the new cards in the Tin of the Pharaoh’s Gods are trying to capture, and, if played the right way, they succeed.

            This is the Day of Storms.

deck_excerpt: Zaborg the Mega Monarch >>>> White Zoa of Dogmatika
deck_description:
Budget-like Deck I have been taking to locals recently
To simply explain the plan here, you want to use Zaborg the Mega Monarch to mill out your opponents Extra Deck, using that to then mill key cards out of your extra deck to usually end on Amorphactor Pain, the Imagination Dracoverlord and a Branded Retribution at minimum.
basic drytron combo applies with some small caveats
-usually you want to open 2-3 names or 1 name and nova to start out, using linkuriboh to put that name in grave and get fodder for a tribute summon
-you want to either open Zaborg or Small world, using Cross-Sheep to fish for Zaborg if need be
typical combo uses names to get a Drytron Mu Beta Fafnir and linkuriboh/cross sheep on field and then ritual summon Drytron Meteonis Quadrantids, then ritual summon zaborg using Mu Beta and Linkuriboh, blowing up Quadrantids, milling your whole ED
-CL 1 Quadrantids, CL2-4 Herald of the Arc Light , CL5 Elder Entity N'tss popping something to chainblock if you're worried
Quadrantids gets you back 2 names, Heralds can fetch you Amorphactor Pain, the Imagination Dracoverlord, Meteonis Drytron, and either of the Drytron lvl 12 rituals, use PSY-Framelord Omega to reset the Mu Beta, you can make Amorphactor and Draconids depending on the combo, fetching Branded Retribution and setting it using Albion's effect in the End Phase.
I use White Relic of Dogmatika  as a Small World bridge for unbricking hands and getting Zaborg, working for most cards in the deck, going from any Drytron to another or fetching Zaborg, while remaining largely on theme and being a good way of outing any big beefy boss monster for cheap (no seriously I've won games solely off of the attack gain effect of Relic)
Side deck is largely a meme for my locals to either go second or clearing out the 2 decks that dont care about their Extra Deck
This is a try for use some gem Knight as support for melodious

Hello everyone,

This is one of my favourite decks I've played so far. I've tested a lot of builds, what works for me and what not as much. These are my tips and suggestions for adjustments or improvements for deck depends what you are gonna play against. 

Against HERO deck - the biggest problem wasn't really Masked HERO Dark Law  but Dark Angel  since you are heavy oriented on your Spells. If you going second, just pray they don't have access to D. Angel or just have a way to summon Mirrorjade the Iceblade Dragon  and basically waste its effect on it. Also Swap out Mudragon of the Swamp  against them. It's useless since Fusion Destiny  is a thing and most of your powerful Fusion monsters are Dark type anyways. 

Against Floowandereeze deck - effect veiler or impermanence on their first summon should do the trick. If you going first have some negs ready for summons mostly. I would recommend swapping out for Horn of Heaven  if you going first (to have at least one more negate). 

Against Bystials (even bystials based) deck - x3 Skull Meister if you are scared to run into them, but just 2 is enough for me. 1 in main since I don't like surprises should be enough. Going first is kinda flip, going second should be much better even tho tear/bystials would be a problem in that case. 

Against Tear/Ishizu (tear based) deck - Don't go second, and if you do, try to bait their negs on Shrouded Dragon eff or if you already have Branded Fusion then something like Aluber or Fallen of Albaz on summon effs. Just play mindgames. Also, in most cases when you going blind and don't know what you playing against, your Super poly will be useless against it, so if you have BEO3, just swap it out for Necrovalley and Predaplant Triphyoverutum . Necrovalley  will hit you too but not as much as them. Yes Triphy is risky and kind of high "cost" but you can easily combo it with either mirror or albion, to clear a board + have a negate either way. Also, activating Necro in first turn after you have your stuff prepared is most-likely to be a GG if they don't have something to clear it up. 

Against DWorld/Danger (Apollousa, Bow of the Goddess  based too) deck - New DWorld decks are crazy but the biggest problem for you is going second. If you can't negate the right stuff with effect veiler/meister/imperm you are gonna have a big problem or just starting with less than 3 cards in your hand. Also, hitting Dangers in opp hand is crucial so a bit of luck too. And also, pray for no Ceruli, Guru of Dark World . Other than that, the match-up is pretty much coinflip but you can get ahold of it really fast when playing against it. Necrovalley would be a good addition too when having second match.

 

I do not prefer main-decking Necro especially when I go blind. It backfired couple of times. I've experimented with 3x Branded Opening and Branded in Red as well. I've bricked a lot of times playing it that way, that's why cuting it to 2 was just right imo.

Gold Sarcophagus  - my reason to play it, is ofc combo with Tri-Brigade Mercourier  -> basically search power, also good bait to negs.

Branded in High Spirits  - personally, I do not like playing it more than 1, since it's not really that often when you can actually play it and even if you do, you can bounce it back to the hand afterwards so playing it with more copies would be a waste of space tbh. 

Despian Tragedy  - 3x is my personal preference. I've experimented with 2x, it works too. You can add one more hand-trap or something else for it if you like. 

Ad Libitum of Despia  and Dramaturge of Despia  - having more than 1 copy of it will brick you for sure. They have awesome effects while used as synchro material - so you basically don't want to see them that often in your hand or even more copies of 'em. 

Fallen of Albaz/Albion the Shrouded Dragon - 3x - this is my another personal preference since having "only" 1x Shrouded Dragon, you want to see this guy in your hand basically every turn. I've played with 2 of each but it was kinda lame and coinflip. Ratio 3 - 1 works better for me. Also, you wanna target Branded Sword from your Deck (not hand) with Shrouded Dragon. If you have Branded Sword in hand while using Shrouded Dragon effect I would recommend you to dump Branded Openingfrom your Deck -> most of the times like 95%, you want to draw card not summon S. Dragon. Edit: Added 1x more Shrouded Dragon, since I've decided to play more than 40 card deck. 

 

Super Polymerization - 2x - Yes "only" 2. I found myself bricking on 3x for some reason. Also you are discarding A LOT with this build - that's why having 3x tragedy is a good thing heh. 1 copy of it wasn't really coming in my hand at all when it was really needed. Having bigger chance to have 1 is always good. So 2x is optimal for me. Don't forget to swap it out when going against Tear decks, it will get only negated/shuffled and won't really work against them sadly. 

Springans Kitt  - 3x is overkill imo. 1x ain't enough, at least not for me. 2x is just right. I mean, you still can play 3x, cut out 1x Tragedy, and try it that way. But with this build, i'm suggesting playing only 2 copies. Edit: Nevermind, 3x is just fine. Playing more than 40 card deck tho. You can still cut it if you want to 2. But I've sided 1x Meister for it. 

Artifact Scythe  + Back to the Front - The reason playing 1x of both is just to scythe lock your opponent. Since you gonna dump scythe to the grave anyways. Either with discards like Super Poly or with Branded Fusion for Albion. You can basically bait your opponent into Scythe but still having the option of Back to the front is nice. Basically you can use it for bringing back fusions like Mirrorjade so, still win-win situation. 

Branded Bond  - I was discussing this with few people if this was good or not as main deck card. You won't see this card even in side deck but hear me out. This card came so clutch in a lot of situations. Especially when it can be used for basically Shrouded Dragon from Grave or banished Fallen of Albaz. Even if you summon Aluber the Jester of Despia  and they negate his effect you can do some sweet combos with this one card in hand - going for one of those two either from hand/grave/banish - summon it and you have another options from there. This card is so underrated imo, even tho it's pretty lit. Also, one copy is just fine, if you want, you can add 2nd but i am not really sure what you gonna swap it for if you want to keep the cards at 40. 

Incredible Ecclesia, the Virtuous  - She is incredible! Quite literally. 1x is enough tho. It's cool to have her 2x but, you can recycle her so having more than 1 would be a waste. Also she is "Light" target for your Branded Fusion as well (if you don't want/don't have your scythe in your deck/hand to be dumped) and it's your search card as well. 

Hand-traps (Meister, Veiler, Imperm) - 1x meister, 2x veiler - reason for this ratio is my pure preference. Veiler is another "Light" target for b fusion + interupt for field. Meister in other hand can be "Dark" target for fusion as well - looking at the Triphy especially and good grave interupt - but still, only 1 against most of decks is just fine. Having eff negs for field worked much better for me, that's why having 2x imperm going second is kinda clutch as well. Why no Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring? She is "FIRE" - that's mostly why not. Why no D.D. Crow? I mean, you can argue it's better than Skull Meister but he is my prefered card, since he is negating the effect from grave. Why no Ghost Belle & Haunted Mansion? - I'm still thinking of adding her x1, but to be completely honest, I can't see her working in my favor going first, so maybe, just maybe, only 1 copy would be good even if going second. Also - "EARTH" won't benefit any of my fusions at all. Edit: Sided Meister, added Ghost Ogre & Snow Rabbit - Not only hand-trap but "LIGHT" target as well. Also Called by the Grave - i think i don't need to explain this one.

 

I'll update the list/description if I add/find something new. If you want have some combos explained, feel free to comment it down below, I'll try to add them here in description.

 

Edit: Added cards to main deck - 1x Branded Retribution
                                                     1x Ghost Ogre & Snow Rabbit 
                                                      1x Called by the Grave 
                                                      1x Albion the Shrouded Dragon 
                                                      1x Springans Kitt 

       Added cards to side deck - 1x Solemn Strike 
                                                   1x Dark Ruler No More 

       Moved cards from main to side - 1x Skull Meister 

       Moved cards from side to main - 1x Branded Retribution 
                                                           1x Albion the Shrouded Dragon 
       Removed from both side/main completely - 1x Horn of Heaven (replaced by 1x Solemn Strike )

Pretty typical Invoked Shaddoll Dogmatika

Standard 9 card Invoked package, it's great already no need to alter it.

A larger 14-card Shaddoll package, the El Shaddoll Fusions grant more consistent access to the extra deck before it's locked.

A quite common dogmatika package, only 2 Ecclesia, the third is unnecessary because of the search effect off of Nadir Servant. Maximus can give more options but loses to Tear(Kitkallos).

Won't see Apollousa too often but is nice for the off scenarios.

Extra deck isn't set or optimized, Harpie's feather duster is busted against a few decks(i.e. large backrow like Labyrinth), MST is always an option, Gagaga Cowboy can burn for 800.

Consider Ash over Effect Veiler, possibly cut a Nibiru.

deck_description:
Zombie Dragonmaid - MD Season 12

Don't forget to check out the gameplay.

Aliens.... Hey I said ALIENS! Not really a Word Yugioh players fear. Sadly Aliens never got the Spotlight they deserved and that's why it's time to change that with this Decklist. Let's see the Details:

 

The Obvious go to Combo

It's obvious that the new Link 3 Cosmic Slicer is the go to card to make in this Deck. He's Mystic Mine on legs (just a little different) and is a additional Normal Summon and a on summon search for A-Counter related cards. This card alone wins you a Duel if played right and it's something Aliens desperately needed to be somewhat relevant again.

Overlord, Dog and Ammonite are the Monsters which give you the summon power to make him. Crop Circles, Recombination Device with Mysterious Triangle and Code A Ancient Ruins combined are the Spells and Traps who enable a easier summon for the Cosmic Slicer too. 

Together with Alien Kid or Planet Pollutant Virus (both searchable through slicer) every Monster of the opponent with A-Counters is changed to defense position and can't activate it's effects.

If the Cards fall right he's on Board as early as turn one and ready to be destroyed by Lightning Storm.

 

Let's be honest that's not enough

Aliens other big boy the Synchro Level 5 Fortress is the other Key Card which enables a lot of Spam and Removal if combined with Code A Ancient Ruins. Alien Ammonite is a easy one Card Combo to make him. Due to the soft once per Turn Nature of every older Alien card you can easily loop Code A with the Fortress to summon the Fortress Synchro boy 3 times in one round and some other dudes on top of that. 

With all that you have a easy OTK line ready at any time, waiting to be deployed and waiting to be removed by Nibiru. 

 

And that's it? 

No not at all. I didn't even mention the A-Counters in all of this. A-Counters when combined with certain Alien Monsters decrease the opponents ATK and DFF by 300 for every A-Counter and every Monster with said effect. Breaking big Tower Monsters (If not unaffected) are easy to be cleared with it since many A-Counter spreading effects are non targeting. 

Monsters infected with A-Counters are also in danger of changing Control to your side of the field with Brainwashing Beam or Alien Hypno. Alien Hypno can steal up to 4 Monsters with no once per turn yet again and Brainwashing Beam acts as interruption. 

The last Cosmic being the Cosmic Horror can tribute over stolen Monsters to remove them for good and Crop Circles achieves similar things. The Fail to find take 2000 damage part in Crop Circles effect is not working anymore due to current official rules preventing that.

 

That's all right? 

Just a few extras left. The lackluster Field Spell is being played at one since it's a perfect return to hand card for the Synchro Fortress amd 1900 ATK sounds better then 1600. Alien Hunter is additional OTK power and kinda bad but always welcome as an option for me to Deal 3200 Damage. Alien Mother is the perfect target to be ditched to the Graveyard to be revived later with Code A. She Combos well with Overlord too, making her a suspicious one of. 

 

Final Words

Aliens are good. They have a lot of interruption ready to be deployed and can easily overwhelm the opponent. The downsides are the absence of any Protection whatsoever. Alien Shocktrooper M-Frame is the only small lifeline they have to recover from Boardwipes. Gaining advantage again when the Field is once broken is difficult too, often leaving them open to be one turn killed after. 

Stealthbuster and Recombination Device are your only real recovery tools and often not enough. 

But don't let all that fool you. Aliens are a force to be reckoned with. With enough practice you can easily aim for Platin League and Higher in Master Duel.  

Try it yourself if you like Aliens like me. They are a fun Counter related strategy that works thanks to modern support. 

Overall Rating: ★★★★☆☆

Just a non-meta Eldlich deck, based on different Eldlich competitive decks.

With vernusylph being fully released and clockwork night being out earth machine is as super consitent and has good grind game as well as a good match up against tear 0

For combos use the earth machine spreadsheet (https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1U3veuvKsbVExKRaDfCDwnoJdaAH6KXe2pZrlFxjAyjw/edit?fbclid=IwAR2x3TwpHyBJr4uS24SBFrkdoRm-hTUHL2rz5FOW1lbpkLAqlEFRqCnNxiQ#gid=667529116) created by Superpeludo

Going to be making another one of these writeups since a lot has changed in the format since the last post. We hopefully will be getting new support soon so a update now sounds decent + it could get more people excited for more future lists. Also I wanted to make a post so MBT finally makes a video about magistus for either one of his two deck shows (TMT or one shot show).

 

Anyways, some notes. This list was specifically crafted to beat Tearelements/ the current meta. It's not a pure spellcaster list like many of you probably hope but rather a build that uses the good cards from the format to setup more interruptions.

 

 

 

Description:

 

Magistus is a lore based - spellcaster archetype that focuses on attaching ED monsters to themselves (similarly to summoning them as their avatars) to do certian things. 

 

 

 

Deck List and Explanation: (I'll be copying a lot of the descirptions from my old post since I'm lazy AF)

 

Magistus Engine: (12)

 

 

3x Zoroa, the Magistus of Flame: Tuner of the deck. Serves as a starter as it can special summon another lv4 spellcaster from your hand/gy or attach Artemis to get to Crowley if you have spellcaster handtraps. 

 

3x Endymion, the Magistus of Mastery:  Starter that gets to Artemis and allows you to cycle through your deck. Also is a water for toad and allows you to toolbox equips to out cards.

 

2x Rilliona: S/T Searcher for the deck. I assume it's pretty clear from the ratios, but the magistus spell lineup has been really hit in this list. The issue is that all the spells involve you actually being able to start playing already and/or involve having another card to combo with it. RIlliona isn't as good as Endymion/Zoroa as a starter and rather works as a great followup play to search Vitra on the turn afterwards. It can work as a starter with the annoying play of: NS Rilliona -> Grab Vitra -> Link into Artemis -> Vitra to revive Rilliona -> Attach Artemis but this play just seems worse then it has to be.

 

2x Crowley: Extender for the deck and the card you'll most likely grab off Artemis. His ability to change attributes comes up if you have two Crowleys on board for Rilliona XYZ (who needs two separate attributes) and for Toadally Awesome. He also is useful for Dharc in the ED.

 

1x Vitra: You need to open up another name for this to be good as it's not a starter like most of the format (looking at you field spells/starter smhh). Extender for the deck

 

1x Trismagistus: Extender that serves as a soul charge.

 

In general, these two aren't great in general and even worse in the current format as they lose hard to Rukkalos (Tearelements boss monster. You know who I mean, I ain't googling the card).

 

Generic Broken Cards: (17)

 

1x Unicorn -> Searches follow up in the way of the Cont spell and also allows you to get a peek at your Opp deck if they hand trap you to Zoroa lock effectively. Also banishes a lot of the 1 of cards that decks are running as we move to more toolbox formats.

 

3x Fenrir -> interruption that searches followup and outs a lot of cards itself. Need I say more?

 

2x Druiswurm/3x Magnumut -> Hits Tears hard and is pretty good in general. Also serves as a Dark for Dharc

 

2x Secret Village of the Spellcasters -> A lot of the format have really good spell cards. Furthermore, a lot of the outs for Zoroa come in the way of spell cards. Vahram isn't enough of a protection (not even close lmao, idk what Konami was thinking giving such a weak protection). 

 

1x Kashtira Birth -> Field Spell that serves as followup. In testing, I have yet to use the banish effect but it might come up?

 

1x Metaverse -> 1 card kills Tearelements. Need I say more? 

 

3x Forbidden Droplet -> Little known fact, our equips are free sends with Droplets after their effects are used. Furthermore, wer run a lot of spells that combo well with droplets and/or have things we don't mind sending to GY. (the two performages come to mind)

 

 

 

Generic Cards:

 

1x Foolish Burial -> to send a performage to have an easy extender. Also can be a play starter when combined with Vitra. Note you can send Trick Clown for a free body if you want to. 

 

Pot of Desires -> Draw 2. You are running duplicates of a lot of cards you need. Typically I either use this to get extenders or hope to get into the good field spells.

 

Spellcaster "Generics":

 

3x Spell Power Mastery -> Our way to search for our starter Endymion 

 

1 ea of Juggler/ Trick Clown/ Hat Tricker -> More extenders to play thru boards. 

 

 

 

ED:

 

1x Aiwass -> Fusion based meta so Aiwass is here. Has a neat effect to give the equipped monster 1k attack/def which comes up once an a while.

 

1x Zoroa, the Magistus of Daimon - Our main t1 board usually revolves around him. Important to realize that Zoroa says the cards don't have to be attached to him to do the floodgate effect and that Zoroa works no matter where the ED monster attempts to activate. Also has a neat reincarnation effect that becomes useful for plays later on and to reestablish the lock. Can be ran at 1 or 2 - up to your preference. (Would RECOMMEND 1 because you need the util in the ED to play through boards!)

 

1x Zeus - It's Zeus. Need I say more? A lot of decks are focused on decent rank 4's so we can rank up into Zeus quite easily to force interruption.

 

1x Bahmaut Shark/Toad - One of the best interruptions that Magistus can make. Just use either Crowley type changed to water + Endymion and/or Jigabyte to make Shark and Toad.

 

1x Feral Imps -> Combo line to make UFD + Toad. I'll go over this line at the end but it's used to search for Jigabyte (note it's a pretty big rank 4 so in testing I've also made it specifically to search for an extender then make Zeus).

 

1x Bagooska - Best Generic rank 4 if you get stopped. Sadly, spellcasters don't have much generic extenders which are also spellcasters themselves. A lot of them involve having something else on the board (Ecclesscia needs an ED monster, Hat Tricker needs two monsters) so if you get stopped and can't make Rilliona or can't make a decent board, go with trusty plan B.

 

1x  Rilliona - Typically the card that allows the search for baby Zoroa. Allows us to consistently go into Zoroa. Remember that this card locks us into Magistus ED monsters. Also has a neat effect to negate a monster on your turn.

 

1x UFD Package - Easy enough to make turn 1 granted you have a way to 3 level 4 bodies (which happens very often). 

 

Combo line to make Toad + UFD: Start with starter (typically Endymion) -> search Crowley. Bring out Crowley and one extender of your choice. XYZ the monsters that aren't able to turn water (if you have jigabyte then use jigabyte as a material since you can only have one on the board) and make feral imps. Feral Imps Search Jigabyte, ss jigabyte into Shark into Toad. Then use Shark + Feral to make UF into UFD.

 

Accesscode/Selene/Dharc -> Halq was banned so we gotta make due with what we have. Crowley being a dark makes Dharc possible for us and a lot of the format currently uses Darks so it works well. Line is simple: Make Dharc, ss a dark from opp gy, make selene, revive from gy or ss from hand, make Accesscode. Two pops + a 5.3k body sounds good to me.

 

2x Artemis - the best equip card that the deck has. It allows the search for any of our Magistus monsters that we need in hand. Honestly, currently the best card in the entire archetype. 

 

 

 

Side deck:

 

Droll still works well with the deck since Crowley needs to discard a spellcaster. Droll isn't to bad into the current format.

 

Vahram/Ninaruru -> Syncro Lock + extra xyz lock or backrow pop

 

HFD -> We still don't have a great way around backrow so 1 HFD in the side to finish up the set of 3 with Vahram/Ninaruru has been the best option so far.

 

LS/Evenly -> Board breakers. Great for forcing up interruption in the form of Cryme in the Tearelements matchup.

 

Summon Limit -> FLOODGATES GO BRRRRRRRRRRRRRRRRRRRRRRRRRRRRRRRRRRRRRRRRRRRRRRRRRRRR. I choose this floodgate as after we establish a board, we don't have to SS a lot. We also can out it ourselves with Droplets.

 

 

 

Anyways, here's my current list that I've been trying out in the YGO Omega competitve ladder. It doesn't feel that bad against most of the meta and does give magistus a fighting chance. Best I've gotten is to 1400 ELO with it which isn't to high but shows that the deck can steal matches against the meta.

 

 

 

Anyways, have a good rest of your day and I hope this helped you all learn some stuff about magistus!

 

Discord Link to the magistus discord: https://discord.gg/kPWcDuXv

deck_description: This deck is inspired by the OCG meta decks. Modified to be compatible with the TCG banlist. Enjoy

Zekkei (ぜっけい) went 6-2 and finished 5 – 8th in “16th Tetsu Champion Ship ~Road to TCS~” which had 141 participants.

Tearlaments had dominated for two consecutive format OCG 2022.07 and OCG 2022.10, before receiving a heavy-handed hit in the OCG 2023.01 Limit Regulation. With Tearlaments Kitkallos forbidden, Tearlaments has to rely on using King of the Swamp to Fusion Summon Tearlaments Rulkallos. King of the Swamp is an Aqua monster and could be used to Fusion Summon Tearlaments Kaleido-Heart, and also opens up the option to go into Grapha, Dragon Overlord of Dark World.

While King of the Swamp is in hand, it could be discarded to add Polymerization from deck to hand. Polymerization could then be played to Fusion Summon Guardian Chimera to destroy cards on opponent’s field.

Running Shaddoll monsters in the Main Deck is also seeing a return for Fusion Summoning El Shaddoll Winda. Shaddoll Fusion in the Side Deck could be boarded in when going second to send a DARK Tearlaments monster from deck to graveyard by Fusion Summoning El Shaddoll Winda, or to send an EARTH Ishizu monster from deck to graveyard by Fusion Summoning El Shaddoll Shekhinaga. The Trigger Effect of the Tearlaments monster or Ishizu monster that was sent to the graveyard could then be activated.
i havent played this game in years, im not sure if this is good.

deck_excerpt: Scythe lock is back, your opponent can't use the extra deck
deck_description:
Hulu went 6- 2 and finished finished 5 – 8th in “16th Tetsu Champion Ship ~Road to TCS~” which had 141 participants.

Spright was the best deck in the OCG 2022.04 format, but has since been dethroned by Ishizu Tearlaments at the end of the format, and then received two waves of hits by the Limit Regulations that follows.

Spright initial end board consist of Toadally Awesome, which became forbidden in the OCG 2022.07 Limit Regulation. Then Spright pivoted over to Union Carrier to equip Dragon Buster Destruction Sword, which became forbidden in the OCG 2022.10 Limit Regulation. With the weakening of Tearlaments in OCG 2023.01, Spright could spring back to the top of the competitive scene.

Artifact Dagda is Spright latest weapon of choice. Artifact Dagda effect would set Artifact Scythe from deck to the field , then during the opponent’s turn, I:P Masquerena effect would Link Summon Sky Striker Ace – Azalea. Upon being Special Summoned, Sky Striker Ace – Azalea effect would destroy Artifact Scythe, which would then Special Summon itself from graveyard and then deny the opponent from Special Summoning monsters from the Extra Deck for the rest of this turn.

Of course the Scythe lock is only useful against decks that rely on Special Summoning from the Extra Deck. Against decks such as Labrynth, I:P Masquerena effect would be used to Link Summon Mekk-Knight Crusadia Avramax or Topologic Zeroboros instead.

Using Cyber-Stein effect to Special Summon Naturia Exterio is also an end board option. Cyber-Stein could be searched out by using Spright Sprind to send from deck to the graveyard, and then using Spright Elf Special Summon from the graveyard. However, Cyber-Stein effect has to be activated before playing Gigantic Spright or Spright Starter as they would prevent Naturia Exterio, a Level 10 Fusion Monster, from being Special Summoned.

Hetawo (ヘタヲ) went 6-1-1 and finished 5 – 8th in “16th Tetsu Champion Ship ~Road to TCS~” which had 141 participants.

Labrynth is a Trap heavy control deck that debut in Deck Build Pack: Tactical Masters, but only became competitive with the addition of Lady Labrynth of the Silver Castle in Darkwing Blast and Big Welcome Labrynth in Photon Hypernova.

Labrynth controls the opponent by using Normal Traps to pick off the opponent’s monsters, and in turn triggers the other Labrynth card effects to gain card advantage.

Hetawo opted for a Rank 4 build, running the full 3 copies of Ariane the Labrynth Servant and Arianna the Labrynth Servant in the Main Deck. Rank 4 opens up the option to go into Number 41: Bagooska the Terribly Tired Tapir, and D/D/D Wave King Caesar into D/D/D Deviser King Deus Machinex, and even Number 77: The Seven Sins. Since these are all Fiend Monsters, they could be Xyz Summoned even while under the restriction placed by Welcome Labrynth.

As mentioned in his tweet (@anohito_YP), Evilswarm Exciton Knight is something that he would like to add to the Extra Deck, a Rank 4 Fiend Xyz Monster that provides a board wipe effect. Chaos Hunter in the Side Deck is something that he would likely cut.

Kusyano (クシャノ) went 10-0 and finished 1st in “16th Tetsu Champion Ship ~Road to TCS~” which had 141 participants.

Spright Tri-Brigade has been around in the metagame since Spright was released back in Power of the Elements, but has been largely overshadowed by Spright, Tearlaments and Kashtira. But the Limit Regulations have dealt a heavy hand to these decks, severely lowering their power level and consistency, allowing for Spright Tri-Brigade to shine.

Tri-Brigade and Spright have a certain amount of synergy that allowed the two themes to flow together and form a congruous strategy. Tri-Brigade Kitt is a Level 2 monster and could be sent to the graveyard with Spright Sprind effect, Tri-Brigade Kitt and Tri-Brigade Kerass are Level 2 monsters and could be Special Summoned by Spright Elf and Gigantic Spright effect, while Nimble Beaver is a Beast monster and could be banished as cost to activate the effect of Tri-Brigade monsters.

Using Spright Starter or Gigantic Spright would restrict the player to only Special Summoning Level/Rank/Link 2 monsters, but that is just a minor inconvenience. Tri-Brigade Kerass is a Level 2 monster, Tri-Brigade Kitt Tri-Brigade Ferrijit the Barren Blossom, Tri-Brigade Bearbrumm the Rampant Rampager and Ancient Warriors Oath – Double Dragon Lords are Link-2 monsters, so they could be Special Summoned as usual. While the player could not end on Apollousa, Bow of the Goddess directly, they could go into I:P Masquerena first, and using I:P Masquerena effect to Link Summon Apollousa, Bow of the Goddess on the opponent’s turn.

deck_excerpt: Want to make your x3 "Immortal Glory" Structure deck a bit more competitive in Masterduel? This deck is perfect for you!
deck_description:
Want to make your x3 "Immortal Glory" Structure deck a bit more competitive in Masterduel? This deck is perfect for you!

The main strategy of this deck is to establish the "Zombie World Lock" board. While Zombie World + Rivalry of Warlords ensures that your opponent only controls only one monster on their field, Doomking Balerdroch allows a negate + banish once per turn. To achieve this board, Zombie World + Doomking have to be present on the field.

As long as you have this set-up, you're likely to win and everything else that you summon on your field is extra defends your "ZWorld Lock."

This ideal board primarily falls to the crux combo piece Uni-Zombie. Uni-Zombie almost single-handedly achieves this end board by milling zombies from the hand or deck (Necroworld Banshee for Zombie World) (Glow-Up Bloom for Doomking), in addition to providing synchro access.

Shiranui Solitaire allows more ready access to the "ZWorld Lock" board, by summoning Uni-Zombie from deck.

Milling as many cards as possible from your deck/hand to your GY enable this strategy. The "Assault Mode" engine supports milling, since a summoned Psi-Reflector easily makes a level 8 Synchro, which would be Chaos Ruler. Chaos Ruler mills 5 from your deck (hopefully zombies) while adding a combo piece to your hand.

If you have extra monsters on field, Vampire Sucker is the ideal monster to summon. She provides more resources to a zombie player by giving the player a free draw anytime a zombie is resurrected from either graveyard. During the standby phase, if Doomking is in the graveyard and there is a Field Spell on the board, it will resurrect itself, which prompts Vampire Sucker's +1 draw effect (chain link 1) and Doomking's banishment effect (chain link 2). Drawing one card and banishing another on the field/graveyard in the standby phase is often devastating. Often in the first turn, Doomking + another zombie is linked away for Vampire Sucker to allow for this chain to occur during your opponent's standby phase.

While this deck is strong and consistent going first, it doesn't do well to interruptions, negates and handtraps. "Pure" Zombieworld is considered "rogue" in the competitive environment of Masterduel that is overrun with Runick, Branded and Adamancipator. If you truly want to upgrade your "Immortal Glory" Structure Deck, perhaps you should pair it up with Eldlich and Branded.

Also, if your normal summon Uni-Zombie is somehow negated pr interrupted, the turn usually ends there. This deck also has difficulty breaking established boards, as it doesn't have much tools to do so.

All in all, this deck is a fun rogue strategy to play, semi-budget (thanks for the Structure Deck Masterduel devs!), and easy to learn.

GLHF Duelists!

Shiranui is a known Duel Links threat but what if I tell you it's actually good in Master Duel/TCG too? I feel like many people don't understand the slower playstyle of Shiranui so I go more into Detail below: 

 

The Starters:

Your obvious goal with this Deck is to get your L2 Spectralsword Tuner into the Graveyard as quickly as possible to get a follow up Synchro summon on the next turn. Note that you can also banish him and use additional effects to get him back to the GY.

Your Number one go to Card for that is the L4 Squire which sets up a first Turn L6 or L7 Synchro Summon. Spiritmaster and Solitaire to some extent can achieve the same with more setup/downsides.

 

But how do I survive if Squire is missing? 

That's were Shiranui is starting to work. They can prevent all damage with the permanent Trap Samsara and have a stronger Icarus Attack with Swallow's Slash (Banish Spiritmaster to destroy up to 3 cards). 

In addition they have Quick Effect Speed summons from Hand and Deck and the L4 Samurai can at quick effect Speed trigger his non targeting Banish if he's being attacked and thus trigger Spiritmaster to interrupt the opponent further.

With that you will be able to survive even against the most Meta oriented Decks with ease. But beware since this strategy falls appart if the opponent summons multiple negates during his turn (Prevent that with Destroy Interruption like Swallow's Slash or Spiritmaster). Having the permanent spell Solemnity active also helps (if it survives). 

 

It's your second turn, what now? 

Now it's Shiranui's time to strike back. Use the Spectralsword in the graveyard to setup a L6 or 8 Synchro play and use the L3 Spectralsword Shade tuner to recycle said Combo back to the field and go into the Synchro 10 Sunsaga and non targeting destroy what's left on the opponents side of the field.

To prevent any follow ups feel free to activate the Shiranui/Mayakashi Trap to prevent any Special summons from anywhere except the grave. 

From this point thanks to strong Recycling and banishing power you can Combo through any of your Shiranui Boss Monsters whenever you like and devastate the opponent's strategy. 

The one strong upside of this Archetype is you never run out of gas. 

 

The Extra Spice

Both Shiranui Style Samsara and Shiranui Style Solemnity are Soft Once per turns. Having more then one active equals more advantage. Imagine Recycling 6 Monsters and Drawing 3 cards in one turn. A pipedream I dream of every day. 

The Link 3 Monster helps Shiranui getting over their once per Turn Special Summon limitation by interrupting the opponent with a summon during their turn. Thanks to the link arrows of her you always find space to summon one Shiranui back from the banished Zone.

 

Final Words

Shiranui is truly fascinating and versatile in it's usage. The Fire Attribut gives them some unique Matchups and big faces if you happen to see Barrier Statue lockdown (They always summon Fire first). 

But like every Zombie Archetype they hard loose against Necrovalley and other Graveyard interruption and sometimes the whole Strategy breaks appart if the key pieces are missing. 

Then again it's a very fun Deck and easily one of my favourites for it's Recycling/Banishing loop. Give it a try if you like if you want to learn a more complex Deck. Understanding all the Combos and when to use them takes time but I easily go into Platin and beyond with this Strategy when it works. 

Sidenote: In Master Duel they even give you a Shiranui Starter Deck with everything except the 2 UR's. Also the Shiranui/Mayakashi Lockdown Trap is still Missing and can be replaced with "Fateful Hour" or simple Boardwipes instead. 

Overall Rating: ★★★☆☆☆

Casual Witchcrafter fusion deck that uses an Albaz package to facilitate plays. Mostly uses Cartesia and Lubellion to bring out Vice-Madame, but has a few other options depending on the situation. A few notes:

  • Vice-Madame is the main boss monster, as the deck's main priority involves summoning her and extending your plays to get either Verre or Haine on the field (ideally with Bystreet for extra protection)
  • You'll mostly be summoning Vice-Madame either through Cartesia's effect or through summoning Lubellion via Branded Fusion and then summoning her through Lubellion's on-summon effect; the other fusion cards are mostly back-up options if neither scenario works out
  • Master of Chaos is only in the deck to be sent off via Branded in High Spirit's effect; any spellcaster fusion who meets the cost requirement can fill this role
  • Quintet is an extra target for Magicalized Fusion and situational board wipe if you use five different spellcasters
  • Edel can be special summoned by Vice-Madame's effect and help get another WC monster on field from the hand (useful if you drew into Verre or Haine)

Legendary Duelists: Duels from the Deep gave the Umi series its boss monster in the form of the attributal floodgate that is Ocean Dragon Lord - Kairyu-Shin , this together with A Legendary Ocean are the main cards you want to see in your hand, the later being able to be searched via Warrior of Atlantis , Terraforming and Ocean Dragon Lord - Kairyu-Shin , Kairyu can also search the insane Fish Sonar that basically searches most of your monsters, you can also use the Omni-negate Electric Jellyfish 's effect to send your Umi and retrieve it with Yorishiro of the Aqua 's GY effect.

Infernalqueen Salmon is also an important card in the deck since this fiendish fish can summon from aynwhere her husband Terrorking Salmon which under A Legendary Ocean means you get a free R4NK like Bahamut Shark into Toadally Awesome or Number 4: Stealth Kragen , Doom Kraken also helps since he can bounce one water monster you control to dodge negates or just re-add to your hand your Queen so you can summon another King next turn. Dream Shark also helps when making R4NKs since its a LV5 that special summons itself if you control a water monster.

Kashtira Ogre is here to give you a free body and banish, Mega Fortress Whale can bombard your opponent's monsters during your battle phase which is also an important aspect of this deck Sea Stealth Attack and Sea Stealth II ,the original one protects your S/T and destroys monsters your waters battle with, while II allows you to summon from hand or grave any water allowing you to bounce with Doom Kraken or Pop with Whale.

Kairyu-Shin's Dark Reef can send your Sea stealths too to summon 2 monsters that list Umi, Rage of Kairyu-Shin pops and disables monsters zones, it should be noted this card can block the extra monster zone killing most link decks (which should be happening if you have your flood [ignore that marincess exists, they arent real and cant hurt you]), the deck can also play under There Can Be Only One and Gozen Match . It should also be noted that Pacifis, the Phantasm City is good in the mirror match, but that means you can only run 2 legendary ocean which means you will be stuck with unsummunable monsters.

There arent that many combos in the deck since most of it is improvisation, you will be putting resources to get Kairyu and Umi on the field as quickly as possilbe.

deck_excerpt: An affordable deck with the dragon destroyer!
deck_description:
Buster Blader is an awesome card! You can build a viable deck for a very affordable price, just $30 in this case (as of December 2022).

If one were to increase the budget a few nice things to add: kaijus, solemn judgments, harpie's feather duster, lightning storm, ash blossom (or other hand traps), linkuriboh.

The main idea behind the deck is to setup a board with "Buster Lock" i.e. both the Buster fusion and synchro monsters on the field at once which act as a one-sided skill drain. The most efficient way of doing so is through the Prologue trap which is run at 3 alongside Whelp and Trap Trick each at 3 which can search it out from the deck. The secondary little Destruction Sword monsters provide nice control effects e.g. locking opponent from extra deck, graveyard or face-up backrow efffects.

The achilles heel of the deck is backrow, hence the 3 dark bribes and copious backrow removal cards.

deck_excerpt: The strongest Madolche build ever has come to life thank to Ishizu cards. Feel the incredible recovery options and the competitive potential
deck_description: Actual meta Madolche deck, only possible because of MAMA expansion. For some combos please look at the youtube video

.Ritual summoning has always been my favorite method of summoning, despite how it is terribly non-meta. However, the Libromancer archetype seemed to be a bit better than other ritual archetypes, with how its main method of ritual summoning is a field spell with no once-per-turn limitation on its summoning effect. They don't need any extra deck monsters, which is why I'm including some Dogmatika cards. If you have Nadir Servant, add that to this deck. The link monsters are just link monsters that I happen to have on hand, otherwise it would be a bit more focused on targets for the Dogmatikas.

1) U want to Summon Superancient Deepsea King Coelacanth to summon 4 FISH type bodys.
- u can send him to the GY with Lifeless Leaffish or Foolish Burial 
- or summon him from the hand with Icejade Tremora or Abyss Keeper 

most likely u will send him to GY. After that u need another LV4 body besides the Lifeless Leaffish. therefore u have Rare Fish (Instant Fusion / Ready Fusion), Silent Angler or the ZS package (ZS - Armed Sage / ZS - Ascended Sage) to summon Coelacanth with Number 60: Dugares the Timeless. (Summon Nr. 60 in the Extra Monster Zone!!)

I like this deck that I have made

Libromancer Origin gives the deck an insane consistency boost by letting you set any Libro S/T which means you have now 12~ ways to get to the field spell via Origin, Terraforming , Drawing it or Libromancer Geek Boy who can be Emergency Teleport 'ed into the field from the deck. Diviner of the Herald is here to add more ways to get to your rituals by sending Herald of the Arc Light , which also makes Diviner a Lv6 that combined with Libromancer Agent or Libromancer Doombroker means you can make Ultimaya Tzolkin which in turn makes Crystal Wing Synchro Dragon . 

This is one of the good ritual archetypes that lowers the minus you'd normally go through when playing a ritual deck, having a re-usable non once per turn ritual spell with Libromancer First Appearance , good disruption with Libromancer Intervention and Libromancer Displaced , and in general good levels.

Your basic combo would be something like:

E-Teli, Origin, Prep and Fire in hand

Origin > Set intervention, E-teli > Geekboy > Add First Appearance, Appearance > Add Agent, Preparation > Add Benten, Fire reveals Benten to special summon > Add dombroker, Agent Reveals Benten to special smmon, Appearance ritual effect tributes Benten for Doombroker > Benten adds Diviner, Normal summon Diviner and send Arc Light making her a LV6 > Arc light adds Firestarter, Diviner and Agent synchro into Ultimaya, Doombroker > Sets Displaced which triggers Ultimaya > Ultimaya summons Clear Wing, Appearance's ritual summon Firestarter using Geek. You now have 1 monster negate, 1 bounce and 1 Omni-negate, you can use Firestarter and Fire to make I:P, after using intervention to summon a libro you can quick-eff make unicorn.

Fisker Whisker from the Edo discord gave me the idea of Artifact Dagda > Artifact Scythe > + I:P which makes Sky Striker Ace - Azalea during the opponent's turn to pop scythe... so kudos to him

deck_excerpt: An updated going 2nd list featuring Duality from Premium Pack 2023 for the OCG Format.
deck_description:
Overview

This Cyber Dragon list focuses on breaking any board going second. Utilising the newly released "Duality", we are able to tribute any Level 5 Light Machine for a Chimeratech Rampage Dragon or Chimeratech Fortress Dragon for a Cyber Twin Dragon. This card allows Cyber Dragons to access their fusions much more easily and is another great tool to add into our arsenal.

Why Forbidden Droplet over Dark Ruler No More?

Forbidden droplet has a nice benefit to send Clockwork Night on the field to grave to allow us to use Machine Duplication again. It being a Quick-Play also allows us to play around certain interuptions like Infinite Impernance targetting a Cyber Dragon Core. It is also a decent interuption if we are ever forced to go first.

Cyber Dragon

1-3x Cyber Dragon
3x Cyber Dragon Core
2-3x Cyber Dragon Herz
1-2x Cyber Dragon Nachster

0-1x Jizukiru, the Star Destroying Kaiju

3x Cyber Emergency
0-3x Clockwork Night
0-1x Overload Fusion
0-1x Cybernetic Overflow
0-1x Cyberload Fusion
0-1x Cyber Revsystem

1-2x Chimeratech Rampage Dragon
1-2x Cyber Dragon Nova
1-2x Cyber Dragon Infinity
1-3x Chimeratech Megafleet Dragon
1-3x Chimeratech Fortress Dragon
1x Cyber Dragon Sieger

1x Salangreat Almiraj
0-1x Relinquished Anima
0-1x Linkuriboh

1x Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder

0-1x Cyber Twin Dragon
0-1x Cyber End Dragon
0-1x Cyber Eternity Dragon

0-1x Spright Elf
0-1x Gigantic Spright

The typical Cyber Dragon core I stick to. Ratios will largely depend on the engines you wish to use.

Machine Duplication

0 or 3x Machine Duplication

Still a good option (even if it conflicts with Clockwork Night) to go into a Cyber Dragon Infinity. Although, it can be risky since it can be easily disrupted with any almost any kind of interacation.

Galaxy Soldier

2-3x Galaxy Soldier

Another good option for going into Cyber Dragon Infinity. Also acts as a secondary target for "Duality"

Duality

2-3x Duality

Duality is an interesting card, it allows you to trade a Level 5 Light Machine for a Chimeratech Rampage Dragon or any of your Chimeratech Contact Fusions into big threats. This allows Cyber Dragons to access their prized fusions much more easily. Worth trying out due to low extra deck investment needed since you will be running most of the fusions in a regular Cyber Dragon deck anyways.

Therion

1-2x Therion "King" Regulus
0-2x Therion Discolosseum
0-1x Terraforming

An omni-negate in Therion "King" Regulus to either break boards or stabilise on the crackback. Good for the long game

Cyberdark

0-2x Cyberdark Claw
1x Cyberdark Chimera

1-2x Power Bond
1x Cyberdark Realm
0-1x Cybernetic Horizon

Power bond into a 4200 ATK Chimeratech Rampage Dragon for 12600 damage? Decent option if you do not mind the bricks in the deck.

Wishlist

A searchable version of Overload Fusion
1 Card Infinity
Easier access to Clockwork Night
Link 1. Even if it has no other effects other than a "Cyber Dragon" on the field or in GY clause.
A field spell
Any support will do tbh

Qli is a tricky archetype, but I enjoy it.

Feedback is always welcome.

  • Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights  search and Stellarknight Delteros  summon Satellarknight Unukalhai  (if you have not used) and send Tellarknight Altea .
  • Summon Gagaga Magician and revives Stellarknight Delteros and Tellarknight Altea .
  • If you have Stellarnova Alpha , link Gagaga Magician , Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights , Stellarknight Delteros  for Apollousa, Bow of the Goddess  and leave Tellarknight Altea .
  • If you do not have, link Tellarknight Altea to make a full Apollousa, Bow of the Goddess .
  • Stellarknight Delteros pull Satellarknight Sirius  to shuffle everything back (except for Tellarknight Altea ) and draw 1 card.
  • Summon Tellarknight Ptolemaeus  (use Tellarknight Altea  if possible and leave 1 Tellarknight for Stellarnova Alpha )

deck_excerpt: "May this weapon strike true. May it be wielded with wisdom. May it be put down when its job is done." -Brok, God of War: Ragnarok
deck_description:
While I was getting immersed in God of War: Ragnarok, I was not emotionally prepared for the tragedy that would cement Odin's status as the biggest @$$hole in all the Nine Realms: the murder of Brok, and how it twisted Sindri into a broken, hateful shell of his former self. Since the brothers' debut in God of War 4, the rugged, foul-mouthed manly man and soft-spoken, germaphobic sensitive soul have wormed their way into our hearts. So it's no surprise that Brok's funeral scene made at least 10 people on every block cry their eyes out. 

 

This is my tribute to Brok the dwarf, an Ishizu Runick deck. Both of the decks feature milling as key components of their overall strategy. While Runicks have Runick Fountain as their main recovery card, Ishizu's new Fairies have Mudora and Agido's retrains for both recursion and interruption of the opponent's plays. So combined with the Ishizu engine, Runick can deck the opponent out much sooner than expected. This deck doesn't use hand traps apart from Kelbek the Ancient Vanguard, so the ideal scenario is you going first.

 

Now before you download this deck profile, make sure to pour one out for our blue brother in arms. After God of War: Ragnarok proved itself to be one of the hallmarks of 2022 for gamers, I refuse to end the year before giving one final requiem for Brok.

 

May this deck profile win true. May it be played with wisdom. May it be sold on eBay when its job is done.

deck_name: MASTER DUEL DIAMOND LABRYNTH TRAP CONTROL
deck_description:
Playing a trap control style in Labyrinth involves building a deck that focuses on using trap cards to disrupt your opponent's plans and gain an advantage in the game. In this playstyle, you will likely include a high number of traps in your deck, as well as monsters that have effects that are triggered by your opponent's actions, such as activating a monster, spell or trap card.

To play this style effectively, it is important to pay attention to your opponent's moves and anticipate what they might do next. For example, if you see that your opponent is setting a lot of spell or trap cards, you might want to consider holding onto your traps until they are activated, so that you can use them to disrupt your opponent's plans. In a different scenario, because Master Duel is in a format where it’s single elimination and most competitive, meta decks use a lot of special summoning, you want to save your monster effects and traps to hit opponent choke points. The great thing about labyrinth is, you can also use your monster effects to react to your opponent's actions, such as ripping a card from your opponent’s hand through Lovely and if applicable, drawing off Arianna.  

In addition to using traps and reactive monster effects to disrupt your opponent's plans, it is also important to have a solid defense to protect yourself from your opponent's attacks. This involves using monsters with high defense points and attack through Archfiend and Sky Prison, or using traps and spells to negate or deflect your opponent's attacks and monster effects through Storming Mirror Force, Called by the Grave and Impermanence. By carefully balancing your offense and defense, you can effectively control the flow of the game and put pressure on your opponent to make mistakes. This build creates a nice oppressive presence through backrow removal and low monster removal by means of Harpie’s Feather Duster, Heavy Storm Duster and the Virus one-ofs.

Maxx "C" is a monster card that has an effect that allows you to draw additional cards from your deck whenever your opponent special summons a monster. This can be a powerful tool for generating card advantage, as it allows you to gain an extra draw each time your opponent special summons a monster.

Pot of Duality is a spell card that allows you to add a card from your deck to your hand, and then shuffle the remaining cards back into your deck. This can be a useful way to search for specific cards that you need in a given situation, as well as thinning your deck to improve your chances of drawing key cards.

Pot of Extravagance is a spell card that allows you to banish a number of cards from your deck, and then draw that same number of cards. This can be a powerful way to search for specific cards and improve your chances of drawing them, as well as thinning your deck to improve the consistency of your draws.

In general, these cards can be powerful tools for improving the consistency and efficiency of your deck, and can be especially useful in trap control decks that rely on having specific cards in hand to disrupt your opponent's plans. By carefully considering how to use these cards in your deck and strategy, you can improve your chances of success in Labyrinth.

In conclusion, this deck is amazing and has done phenomenal for me. I am currently 9-0 with this deck; I don’t know how impressive that may be for you, the individual reading this, but anything above gold in Master Duel is sweaty! 

Thank you for your time! :)

This deck is focusing on shutting down your opponents during their turn/turn zero; a strategy ursarctics excel above other archetypes.

Premises:

▪Always pick going second

▪Works best against meta decks

▪This is a best of 3 deck

▪ You know what cards you have to silence

Guidance:

▪Use dimshifter in their mainphase, so you can chain your lvl 7 bears to get materials into the grave, circumventing dimshifter. Alternatively you can wait for gamma to resolve.

▪Hop ear almost guarantees ShenShen turn zero, so you basically have 6 dimshifters.

▪Gaia is your bears tribute fodder. Works even under your dimshifter

▪Your handtraps can mostly be tributed from hand too for maximum possible consistency

▪Use polar>tanus>bilis early, to get advantage and fulfilling the condition for your big bears (walking MST, Book of Moon and D.D.Crow)

▪Phantazmay is a godsend by adding carddraw and shuffling back Driver/BLS

▪You can make fleur/Chengying/Shenshen or go for other lvl 6-11, depending on enemies deck and your needs.

deck_excerpt: I wish there was a way to shorten the deck name.
deck_description:
There's a lot of archetypes here, you've likely noticed. The main strategy is to fusion summon a bunch of boss monsters, preferrably ending with monsters such as Mirrorjade the Iceblade Dragon, El Shaddoll Winda, and Invoked Mechaba. I'll go though each of the archetypes and why they're here.

Branded: Just having branded fusion in your hand allows you to get a monster from your deck to the graveyard easily, as well as calling upon Mirrorjade to strengthen your board. Many branded fusion monsters have effects when sent to the graveyard, allowing them to synergize with Dogmatika, and Branded Lost stops your opponent from negating your fusion summons and allows you to search a monster that mentions Fallen of Albaz when you fusion summon any monster, allowing you to get an extra card into your hand without much difficulty.

Invoked: Mechaba's just an annoyance to a lot of decks, so we may as well add them for the extra negate/banish. Their effect requires a card to be discarded, but that's ok, you can discard a Shaddoll or something else with a graveyard effect. Invocation allows you to recycle materials from the graveyard to fusion summon, and the field spell magical meltdown also protects your effects that fusion summon monsters.

Dogmatika: As these cards like to lock you out of the extra deck, try to use Dogmatika cards at the end of your turn whenever possible. Mostly these are just here to send Branded and Shaddoll fusion monsters from the extra deck to the graveyard that way you can use their searching effects.

Elementsaber: The Invoked and Shaddoll archetypes can use materials from the graveyard to fusion summon, and these materials are usually dependant on the attribute of one material, so if you can get elementsabers into your graveyard, you can use those as whatever attribute you need. Palace of the Elemental Lords is the card that makes this work, really. It will boost all of your monsters' attack and defence for each attribute in your graveyard, although, that doesn't mean a lot. What this deck really aims for is the ability to search any elementsaber monster from your deck, and to be able to send elementsabers from the deck to the graveyard when you would normally send them from the hand. When you activate your Palace, use it to find Elementsaber Lapaulia Mana. You'll have to skip the battle phase of your next turn, but that's a small price to pay. Then, use Lapaulia Mana's effect to special summon itself from your hand, and to send the other two elementsaber monsters from your deck to the graveyard. I'm using Makani and Lapaulia as fodder for this, but you can switch them out for other elementsabers depending on how you want to use Lapaulia Mana's effect. Anyways, congrats, you now have a decently strong, protected monster and to monsters in the graveyard that can be any element of your choice.

Shaddoll: All shaddol monsters have some sort of effect when sent to the graveyard, so with the other archetypes allowing you to send them from the deck and extra deck to the graveyard, and discarding them, then you'll get these effects often. You can also set up a Winda lock at the end of your turn just to annoy your opponent.

This deck looks a lot more complicated than it actually is, once you get into it, but do try to figure out some combos before you play it. This decklist is legal in both the TCG and in Master Duel (Maybe OCG too but I don't know what the banlist is like there). Have fun if you do try this deck!

Can i have a yosenju without the mayo please.

Speedroid has long been a favourite of mine, jumping into relevancy from time to time. This deck can out of nowhere steal games from your opponent if you play your cards well, and mostly if your opponent has no clue what you're doing. Being an all-wind deck and having 99% of your deck be searchable you can dodge annoying matches such as Floowandereeze at locals with ease. Not only that but with lots of high level monsters being viable this format means Speedroid Maliciousmagnet can quickly steal a nasty kashtira monster your opponent controls or rulkarros in order to synchro into kitedrake or shenshen respectively in order to deal with your opponent.

This deck does not have a great grind game, but if games tend to get to time often at your locals like mine I put in Hi-Speedroid Kendama , but this can easily be replaced for a copy of Adamancipator Risen - Raptite in order to have interruption in the form of a D.D. crow against decks such as Tearlaments or other decks that have key pieces in the graveyard. 

As always this side and main deck flex spots are catered more towards my locals, so feel free to experiment with them. If you have any feedback or other ideas feel free to comment them down below! I'll definitely revise the deck once the gold pride archetype is fully revealed and if there's any more synergy between them!

deck_excerpt: A solid foundation for Buster Blader!
deck_description: The deck list I used when first learning Buster Blader. Relatively affordable with all of the critical pieces present. The deck establishes Buster Lock via the archetype's fusion and synchro cornerstones which shuts down opposing monsters, ideally via the Prologue trap searchable through Whelp or Trap Trick. The deck is quite consistent, albeit vulnerable to backrow hence the triple MSTs and Dark Bribes (replace with Solemn Judgments if budget allows).
when givin' the chance, the board-state will over-whelm all who enter the dojo. beware the samurai.

The goal is to banish and reshuffle your banished cards. It makes for a great way to build up life points all while annoying the opponent. On the norm you can win anytime you want but this deck is mainly made to irritate whoever you're playing against. Plus as previously stated super cheese way of gaining life points without trying. So try it out and have fun with it ❤️

deck_name: Dark Armed Duelist October 2022 Deck Profile
deck_excerpt: Dark Armed Duelist October 2022 Deck Profile
A fun high gold to low plat deck for when you feel like playing something more casual.
deck_description:
This deck is based off of my own lunalight deck in Master Duel with the adition of a few cards that I don't have but feel like they should help, I've been experimenting with Lunalights for a few days now and have come to this deck list, this deck isn't super-meta and will lose to top tier decks about 2 out of 3 times, but since most of those are in high plat you can expect a win rate of about 60 to 70 percent once you learn the deck if you're in gold or low platinum,

Your best play would usually be summoning Panther Dancer with Kaleido Chick as a fusion material substitute and Blue Cat as the other material, then reviving Blue Cat to boost Panthers attack to 5600 and then attacking every monster your oponent controls twice each which should put you in the OTK range against most decks, but in my experiance all of your fusion monsters have some use, even Cat Dancer, so they are all worth running at 3 if you have them,

Other good plays involve using Crimson Fox as a fusion material to lower one of your oponents monsters to 0 and set up some protection for yourself or going straight into Leo Dancer for none targeted destrustion of all of your oponents special summoned monsters, Leo Dancer can of course OTK too but between the harder summoning condition and needing to use more reasources to summon it Panther Dancer is usually better.

This decks bigest weakness is its lack of consistency, sometimes you'll be able to summon anything you want turn 1 other times you'll need to stall and set up your grave for Wolf who is esentially a continuous archetypal Miricle Fusion when in the pendulum zone,

P.S. I'd sugest filling the rest of the extra deck with generic link monsters that you think might be useful.

P.S. You might also consider removing the 2 Purple Butterflies and running 3 Tigers but honestly Tiger isn't as useful as you'd imagine so if you didn't get 3 from pulling packs there's really no reason to waste reasources building more, and if you didn't even get even 1 you can just not run it.

deck_excerpt: This deck is nuts and can deliver powerful answers in runick matchups, also has a strong going second game plan as well.
